    # [Scene: Quay — Night: The Storm]
    hide nyla_torres
    hide maya_serrin
    hide aiden_koa

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Full orchestral dissonance; drums like pounding ocean]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Metal tearing, the scream of ropes, breaking wood, alarms blaring]
    "Narration:"
    "The engineered wall takes the blow. Maya Serrin feel each strike reverberate through your chest as if someone is pounding a fist against your ribs. The instruments that Nyla and the auditors installed feed you numbers that flash like lightning — pressures, flow vectors, sediment displacement."
    "But the sea is not merely pressure charts. Somewhere off the settled channel, a sandbar that had been an old marker for generations shifts. Alk lines of current that Maya Serrin had no authority over reconfigure"
    "themselves in minutes. The conservation of force moves sand like money being redistributed; the sandbar breaks into a new geometry. It funnels a chaotic, angry surge along a path that intersects the little slip where the"
    "older boats have been moored — the hulls of the co-op's oldest crafts, the ones with patched ribs and names carved in block letters."
    "A sound like corrugated metal folding onto itself rakes the night. Ropes snap. A crane that had been securing a cluster of skiffs groans and collapses. The older boats — the ones that didn't have the"
    "luxury of modern reinforcement and had relied on the town's knowledge of tidal moods — are struck broadside by a slap of water and slammed against one another and the quay."
    "Maya Serrin move, because moving is the human equivalent of prayer. Volunteers and fishers pour out into the rain. Maya Serrin taste copper and oil on the wind. Nyla is shouting coordinates into a radio as"
    "the auditors try to document, to timestamp; Dr. Elena Park's engineers are barking orders into headsets, their lights harsh and useless against the raw physics unfolding."
    "Aiden Koa's voice breaks through the roar in a call that is both command and plea. 'Hold! Pull lines! Save what you can!' He is everywhere at once — cursing, hauling, trying to wedge a hand where his father used to work with two steady palms."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A terrible, timber-crushing crack; a hull breaks free and flips, exposing ribs and the names the old man painted in the day he christened her.]

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_5 at full_bg
    "Narration:"
    "The engineered segments did what they were built to do: they kept the flood from breaching town quays, prevented roads from washing away, and kept the worst of the surge from swallowing whole neighborhoods. But what"
    "they did not — could not — prevent was the redirection of the sea's appetite."
    "By dawn, the tally is a ledger of cultural losses: three small boats broken beyond repair, another five with shattered keels, nets ruined, old gear catalogued in the bright light like archaeological artifacts. The co-op stands at the quay with hands on hips, faces hollowed by exhaustion and disbelief."
    # [Scene: Quay | Dawn — Aftermath]

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_6 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse strings; a single, slow piano note repeats like a metronome]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low, continuous sea; the human murmur of organized grief]
    "Narration:"
    "Maya Serrin walk among the boats. The smell of diesel and seaweed is thick; you can feel the grain of splintered wood under your boots. Each name painted on a hull is like a small personal history that you can no longer set right with legislation."
    "Aiden Koa stands stooped over a broken skiff, hands in the rim of the boat as if he could hold the fragments together by will. When he looks up, his eyes are ocean-deep and exhausted."
    show aiden_koa at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aiden_koa "Some things can't be legislated back, Maya Serrin."
    "Narration:"
    "Maya Serrin want to answer with the ordinance, with the auditors and the escrow and the promise of remediation funds. Maya Serrin want to quote the clause that forces the firm to pay for replacement hulls,"
    "temporary income assistance, the apprenticeship funds for youth to learn boat-repair. Those are real, practical measures. They matter."
    "But the sound of his words is not about money. It's about ritual and touch — the knowledge in a fisher's hands that doesn't translate into contracts. It is about the early mornings and the practiced"
    "way his mother braided rope. It is about the sound of cleats on wet timber that signaled the day and the place where people met one another."
    "Narration:"
    "Maya Serrin kneel beside him without meaning to, because proximity is the only thing you can offer that doesn't require pages of legalese. Your parka absorbs rain; your hands smell of salt and crushed cordgrass. You are tired in a way that has nothing to do with sleep."
    show maya_serrin at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_serrin "We can fund replacements. We can establish apprenticeships. We can—"
    "Your voice fractures on the last word."

    aiden_koa "We can fix things that money can touch. We can't fix mornings that changed. We can't legislate back the way the bay used to lull people awake. The ordinance won't bring back the exact sound the boat used to make when she slid past the pier."
    "Narration:"
    "The town's political victory sits next to the taste of loss: a brass victory coin that tastes like iron. People will vote tomorrow on small amendments; auditors will be hired; the escrow will move. Dr. Elena"
    "Park will be in the papers with her team, hailed for preventing the worst. Mayor Hale will give a speech about the resilience of Saltwood. Nyla will keep the feeds live, the data a litany that"
    "cannot be erased."
    "But there is a new line in the ledger now: the human ledger. It keeps a different accounting. Maya Serrin can write checks and sign enforcement orders, but the daily, intimate rhythms of the co-op's life have been changed in a night."
    hide aiden_koa
    hide maya_serrin

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single, unresolved chord held and then allowed to fade into silence]
    "Narration:"
    "Maya Serrin are left with a victory that tastes metallic and terrible. You did what you believed to be right — you made binding clauses; you made the process visible; you empowered the community to monitor"
    "and enforce. That work will protect lives, and for many that is more than enough. But as Maya Serrin watch men and women you love wrap their hands around splintered ribs and count gutted nets like"
    "inventory, you feel an absence that will not be felled by ordinances."
    "Aiden Koa steps closer and lays a hand, callused and warm, on Maya Serrin's shoulder. It is neither a demand nor a comfort; it is an acknowledgment of shared consequence."
    show aiden_koa at left:
        zoom 0.7

    aiden_koa "You carry the town's weight well, Maya Serrin. But some loads we didn't know would be added were all ours to carry."
    "Narration:"
    "There will be hearings. There will be repair lists and fund disbursements and a public timeline for restitution. Nyla will archive every timestamp. Dr. Elena Park will answer questions and sign checks. Mayor Hale will soothe the town with reason."
    "Maya Serrin will return to the Tide Research Station the next day and keep watching the feeds, because watchfulness is the only thing you are sure of. Maya Serrin will teach apprentices how to splice rope and how to read a tide that will no longer be quite the same."
    "But tonight, on the quay, Maya Serrin let the cold in. The victory you engineered has a fracture running through it; it will not be invisible to the people you love."
    hide aiden_koa

    scene bg ch12_f99e88_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Minimal; a low wind instrument whispers a lament]
    "Narration:"
    "Maya Serrin turn your face to the sea. The wind takes the salt and the promise both and throws them outward. Maya Serrin think of Old Man Cala's stories — how he used to talk about"
    "tides as living things with memory. Tonight, they felt less like memory and more like a ledger being rewritten against people's rhythms."
    "Maya Serrin press your thumb against the tide-watch at your wrist. The brass is heavy with a new kind of knowledge: that governance and love are not the same; that saving homes does not always save the meaning stitched to them."
    "Maya Serrin breathe in. Maya Serrin let the town's mixed aftermath settle around your shoulders like wet cloth."
